04393nam a22006375i 9780674039612DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222004mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740396127 a10.4159/97806740396122doi  a(DE-B1597)574411  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQL737.P96 ǂb K56 2004eb 7aNAT0020002bisacsh04a599.88/159/096  aWT 37392rvk0(DE-625)rvk/151997:134641 aKING, Barbara J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Dynamic Dance :bNonvocal Communication in African Great Apes /cBarbara J. KING. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (301 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- t1 Social Communication as Dance -- t2 Gesture and Dynamic Systems Theory -- t3 Gesture in Captive African Great Apes -- t4 Gesture in Wild African Great Apes -- t5 The Evolution of Gesture -- t6 Imagined Futures -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMother and infant negotiate over food; two high-status males jockey for power; female kin band together to get their way. It happens among humans and it happens among our closest living relatives in the animal kingdom, the great apes of Africa. In this eye-opening book, we see precisely how such events unfold in chimpanzees, bonobos, and gorillas: through a spontaneous, mutually choreographed dance of actions, gestures, and vocalizations in which social partners create meaning and come to understand each other. Using dynamic systems theory, an approach employed to study human communication, Barbara King is able to demonstrate the genuine complexity of apes' social communication, and the extent to which their interactions generate meaning. As King describes, apes create meaning primarily through their body movements--and go well beyond conveying messages about food, mating, or predators. Readers come to know the captive apes she has observed, and others across Africa as well, and to understand "the process of creating social meaning." This new perspective not only acquaints us with our closest living relatives, but informs us about a possible pathway for the evolution of language in our own species. King's theory challenges the popular idea that human language is instinctive, with rules and abilities hardwired into our brains. Rather, The Dynamic Dance suggests, language has its roots in the gestural "building up of meaning" that was present in the ancestor we shared with the great apes, and that we continue to practice to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aNATURE / Animals / Primates.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674039612zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674039612423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674039612/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK